I constructed and compared three embedding models (TF-IDF, Word2Vec, and SBERT) using hybrid weighting, L2 normalization, and UMAP dimensionality reduction to analyze semantic similarity in the social welfare domain.
When the silhouette coefficient remained negative, I traced the cause to the curse of dimensionality and applied UMAP to recover distance discriminability, raising the coefficient to about 0.45. The study evaluates clustering performance through silhouette coefficients and cohesion metrics to propose the optimal embedding methodology for a domain-specific synonym dictionary.
